1. Use a more descriptive variable name instead of `n` for the array length. For example, `arrayLength` or `size` would be more clear. This improves code readability.

2. Consider extracting the swap logic into a separate method. This would make the `bubbleSort` method more concise and readable. For example:

```java
private void swap(int[] array, int i, int j) {
    int temp = array[i];
    array[i] = array[j];
    array[j] = temp;
}
```

Then in `bubbleSort`, you can call `swap(array, j - 1, j);` instead of the swap logic.

3. The print statement `System.out.println("Hello World!");` seems unrelated to the bubble sort logic. Consider removing it or moving it outside the `bubbleSort` method for clarity.

4. If you want to make the sorting more efficient, you can add a flag to track if any swaps were made in the inner loop. If no swaps occur, the array is already sorted and you can break out of the outer loop early. This optimization avoids unnecessary iterations.

```java
boolean swapped;
for (int i = 0; i < arrayLength - 1; i++) {
    swapped = false;
    for (int j = 0; j < arrayLength - i - 1; j++) {
        if (array[j] > array[j + 1]) {
            swap(array, j, j + 1);
            swapped = true;
        }
    }
    if (!swapped) {
        break;
    }
}
```

